  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The effort required for creating the Viability Assessment depends on several factors:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The extent of technical risk on the project (it is worth investing more effort in frequent and thorough viability&#xD;
        assessments on high risk projects than where technical risk is low)&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The ease and speed with which the reviewers can become familiar with all relevant documentation&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The size and complexity of the project.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    On a small project, two people may conduct a viability assessment in half a day each (i.e., 1 person day effort).&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    On a large project, external assessors in a workshop format often perform a viability assessment.&amp;nbsp; The effort can&#xD;
    be estimated from the number of attendees, and the duration of the workshop.&amp;nbsp; For example, 5 people for a 2-day&#xD;
    workshop, with another day preparation and follow up, i.e., 15 effort days.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    For estimation purposes, the effort required for assessing viability and updating the Viability Assessment can&#xD;
    sometimes be combined with other review effort at each project checkpoint.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:ContentDescription>
